I&#x27;m surprised that the C++ code is not using the RAII idiom in some obvious places.<p>For example: <a href="https://github.com/facebook/rocksdb/blob/master/db/db_impl.c" rel="nofollow">https://github.com/facebook/rocksdb/blob/master/db/db_impl.c</a><p>There are many places with bracketed calls to mutex_.Lock and mutex_.Unlock().<p>An example:<p><pre><code>      mutex_.Unlock();
      LogFlush(options_.info_log);
      env_->SleepForMicroseconds(1000000);
      mutex_.Lock()
</code></pre>
Why didn&#x27;t the authors use the RAII idiom here? Even if there are no exceptions expected, the code would still be simpler and less error prone by using a guard object.
